01_java_main.description:
A Java program starts from a `public static void main(String[] args)` method.

```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("boot");
    }
}
```

`public` makes the method accessible, `static` means the JVM can call it without an instance, and `String[] args` receives command-line arguments.

04_spring_di.description:
Spring prefers constructor injection because dependencies become explicit and the object can start fully initialized.

```java
@Service
class OrderService {
    private final PaymentClient paymentClient;

    OrderService(PaymentClient paymentClient) {
        this.paymentClient = paymentClient;
    }
}
```

05_web_controller.description:
A controller should stay thin. It receives the HTTP request, delegates business logic to a service, and returns a response.

```java
@GetMapping("/users/{id}")
UserResponse get(@PathVariable Long id) {
    return service.find(id);
}
```

06_jpa_entity.description:
A JPA entity represents a row identity over time. Its lifecycle matters more than just its current field values.

```java
@Entity
class Member {
    @Id @GeneratedValue
    Long id;
}
```

An entity changes state from transient to managed to detached depending on the persistence context.

07_transaction_boundary.description:
A transaction should wrap a unit of work that must succeed or fail together.

```java
@Transactional
public void transfer(...) {
    withdraw();
    deposit();
}
```

Without one boundary, partial writes can escape when an error happens in the middle.

08_spring_test.description:
Not every test needs the full application context. Slice tests load only the layer you care about and keep feedback fast.

```java
@WebMvcTest(UserController.class)
class UserControllerTest { }
```
